      <hedline>
        <hl1>Eureka! A Key to the Code of Life</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Geoffrey James letter on June 27 article questions announcement that human genome has been mapped when 10 percent of genome remains unsequenced; drawing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Genetic Code of Human Life Is Cracked by Scientists'' (front page, June 27):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Genetic Code of Human Life Is Cracked by Scientists'' (front page, June 27):</p>
        <p>Does anyone else think it's ridiculous to announce that the human genome has been mapped when there's more than 10 percent left to go? Has our scientific community become so slipshod that it considers less than 100 percent good enough to be considered a job well done?</p>
        <p>What's next? Will we have to rewrite the history books to make Apollo 10, not Apollo 11, the first flight to land on the Moon?</p>
        <p>GEOFFREY JAMES  Hollis, N.H., June 27, 2000</p>
      </block>
